.TH "REQUEST.ARRAYBUFFER" "3JS" "November 7, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Request.arrayBuffer \- Request: arrayBuffer() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This feature is available in Web Workers.
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]arrayBuffer()\f[B]\f[R] method of the \f[CR]Request\f[R]
interface reads the request body and returns it as a promise that
resolves with an \f[CR]ArrayBuffer\f[R].
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
arrayBuffer()
.EE
.SS Parameters
None.
.SS Return value
A promise that resolves with an \f[CR]ArrayBuffer\f[R].
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown for one of the following reasons:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
The request body is disturbed or locked.
.IP \(bu 2
There was an error decoding the body content (for example, because the
\f[CR]Content\-Encoding\f[R] header is incorrect).
.RE
.TP
\f[B]RangeError\f[R]
Thrown if there is a problem creating the associated
\f[CR]ArrayBuffer\f[R] (for example, if the data size is too large).
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] myArray = \f[B]new\f[R] Uint8Array(10);

\f[B]const\f[R] request = \f[B]new\f[R] Request(\(dq/myEndpoint\(dq, {
  method: \(dqPOST\(dq,
  body: myArray,
});

request.arrayBuffer().then((buffer) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[I]// do something with the buffer sent in the request\f[R]
});
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Response.arrayBuffer()\f[R]
